The '''Medical Council of Jamaica''' is the licencing body for doctors in the Caribbean nation of [[Jamaica]].

Doctors in Jamaica are required to take [[continuing medical education]] courses to keep their licences.<ref>{{cite news
|first=Lowrey
|last=Chin
|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/columns/JA-s-health-care-in-good-hands_11410345
|title=JA's health care in good hands
|date=May 7, 2012
|newspaper=Jamaica Observer
|accessdate=May 23, 2012}} Interview with Dr Aggrey Irons, Medical Association of Jamaica president and psychiatrist. "Continuing education is mandatory - Jamaican doctors must complete in excess of 20 hours on Continuing Medical Education (CME) in order to renew their annual registration with the Medical Council of Jamaica," he [Irons] pointed out.</ref> <ref>{{cite news
|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080425/news/news10.html
|title=Fraud docs pose public danger warns medical council
|first=Tendai 
|last=Franklyn-Brown
|newspaper=Jamaica Gleaner 
|date=April 25, 2008
|quote=Dr Muriel Lowe, registrar of the Medical Council of Jamaica, says unlicensed 
doctors using fraudulent registration numbers pose an imminent threat to public safety.
|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> 

In 2004, amendments to the country's ''[[Medical Act (Jamaica)|Medical Act]]'' increased the number of non-doctors on the council.<ref name="observer20041010">{{cite news
|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/67392_Public-to-have-more-say-on-medical-council
|title=Public to have more say on medical council
|first=Dwight
|last=Bellanfante
|newspaper=Jamaica Observer
|date=October 10, 2004
|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> 
 
The Medical Council's chairman is Dr [[John Hall (Jamaican physician)|John Hall]], a consultant [[neurologist]] and former chairman of the department of medicine at the [[Kingston Public Hospital]] in Kingston, Jamaica.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Medical-Council-head-Dr-Hall-sounds-positive-note_11508604
|title=Medical Council head Dr Hall sounds positive note
|date=May 21, 2012
|work=Jamaica Observer
|accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref>

The [[Medical Association of Jamaica]], a different organisation, is the voluntary professional and advocacy body for doctors in Jamaica.

